body:
This commit: https://github.com/Jaennaet/pISSStream/commit/0f2bd967791df6c8546090ed463bfcf55b0ffbe4#diff-6c97621f1c546b957eb8925c0a1ba3cb0b26e51b2b4b46445985849da9d1af2dL23-R174

Added `TIME_000001` to the Lightstreamer subscription. I’m not entirely sure of the intent, but it has the unintended side effect of generating ~1KB/s of constant incoming network traffic of high-frequency time events that aren’t actually needed.

This hurts efficiency and somewhat defeats the purpose of using a low-bandwidth stream that only delivers relevant events. Without this subscription, pISSStream listens only for the `NODE3000005` (Urine Tank) event, which has an extremely low bit rate and is impressively efficient.

After running pISSStream continuously for a little over a week, I noticed it had downloaded 625MB of data. Not horrible, but a bit unnecessary for a lightweight, always-running daemon for humor purposes. While not a critical issue, it’s an inefficiency that could be avoided.


In the meantime I'm using [swiftbar](https://github.com/swiftbar/SwiftBar) to just re-create pISSStream using this node script:
```
var Ls = require('lightstreamer-client-node');

var sub1 = new Ls.Subscription("MERGE",["NODE3000005"],["Value", "Status", "TimeStamp"]);

sub1.addListener({
    onItemUpdate: function(obj) {
      const percentage = obj.getValue('Value') + '%';
      console.log(`🧑‍🚀🚽${percentage} `);
      process.exit(0);
    }
});

var client = new Ls.LightstreamerClient("http://push.lightstreamer.com","ISSLIVE");

client.connect();
client.subscribe(sub1);%
```

That uses very little network traffic, though it does re-setup the connection every minute, so not really comparable to pISSStream.
